# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: render-cloud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:render-cloud/background-process] A **background process** is a computer process that runs *behind the scenes* (i.e., in the background) and without user intervention.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Typical tasks for these processes include logging, system monitoring, scheduling, and user notification.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] On a Windows system, a background process is either a computer program that does not create a user interface, or a Windows service.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] The former are started just as any other program is started, e.g., via Start menu.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Windows services, on the other hand, are started by Service Control Manager.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] In Windows Vista and later, they are run in a separate session.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] On a Unix-like system, a daemon would be a background process.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] However, in a shell that supports job control, a process that is in a process group whose process group ID differs from its terminal group ID (TGID) would be a background process.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] (The TGID of a process is the process ID of the process group leader that opened the terminal, which is typically the login shell.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] The TGID identifies the control terminal of the process group.) This type of process is unable to receive keyboard signals from its parent terminal, and typically will not send output to that terminal.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] This more technical definition does not distinguish between whether or not the process can receive user intervention.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Although background processes are typically used for purposes needing few resources, any process can be run in the background, and such a process will behave like any other process, with the exceptions given above.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] In Windows NT family of operating systems, a Windows service is a dedicated background process.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] A Windows service must conform to the interface rules and protocols of the Service Control Manager, the component responsible for managing Windows services.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Windows services can be configured to start when the operating system starts, and to run in the background as long as Windows runs.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Alternatively, they can be started manually or by an event.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Windows NT operating systems include numerous services which run in context of three user accounts: `System`, `Network Service` and `Local Service`.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] These Windows components are often associated with Host Process for Windows Services: svchost.exe.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Since Windows services operate in the context of their own dedicated user accounts, they can operate when a user is not logged on.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Before Windows Vista, services installed as "interactive services" could interact with Windows desktop and show a graphical user interface.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] With Windows Vista, however, interactive services became deprecated and ceased operating properly, as a result of Windows Service Hardening.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] A daemon is a type of background process designed to run continually in the background, waiting for event(s) to occur or condition(s) to be met.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] When launched with the *daemon* function, daemons are disassociated from their parent terminal.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] From a Unix command line, a background process can be launched using the "&" operator.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] The *bg* command can resume a suspended job (sending SIGCONT), running it in the background.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Using the *fg* command will also set the foreground process group of the controlling terminal of the session to the process group of the job, bringing the job into the foreground.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] The *jobs* command will list all processes associated with the current terminal and can be used to bring background processes into the foreground.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] When a login session ends, via explicit logout or network disconnection, all processes, including background processes, will by default be terminated, to prevent them from becoming orphan processes.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Concretely, when the user exits the launching shell process, as part of shutdown it sends a *hangup* signal (SIGHUP) to all its jobs, to terminate all the processes in the corresponding process group.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] To have processes continue to run, one can either not end the session, or end the session without terminating the processes.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] A terminal multiplexer can be used to leave a session running but detach a virtual terminal from it, leaving processes running as child processes of the session; the user can then reattach session later.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Or, termination can be prevented by either starting the process via the nohup command (telling the process to ignore SIGHUP), or by subsequently running `disown` with the job id, which either removes the job from the job list entirely, or simply prevents SIGHUP from being sent.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] In this example running on Unix, the *sleep* utility was launched into the background.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Afterward, the *ps* tool was run in the foreground, where it output the below text.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Many newer versions of smartphone and PDA operating systems now include the ability to start background processes.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Due to hardware limits, background processes on mobile operating systems are often restricted to certain tasks or consumption levels.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] On Android, CPU use for background processes may be bounded at 5–10%.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] Applications on Apple's iOS are limited to a subset of functions while running in the background.
[src:render-cloud/background-process] On both iOS and Android, background processes, as well as background or unused apps, can be killed by the system if they are using too much memory or too much battery power.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:render-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] A **dedicated hosting service**, **dedicated server**, or **managed hosting service** is a type of Internet hosting in which the client leases an entire server not shared with anyone else.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] This is more flexible than shared hosting, as organizations have full control over the server(s), including choice of operating system, hardware, etc.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] There is also another level of dedicated or managed hosting commonly referred to as complex managed hosting.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Complex managed hosting applies to both physical dedicated servers, hybrid server and virtual servers, with many companies choosing a hybrid (combination of physical and virtual) hosting solution.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] There are many similarities between standard and complex managed hosting but the key difference is the level of administrative and engineering support that the customer pays for – owing to both the increased size and complexity of the infrastructure deployment.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] The provider steps in to take over most of the management, including security, memory, storage and IT support.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] The service is primarily proactive in nature.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Server administration can usually be provided by the hosting company as an add-on service.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] In some cases a dedicated server can offer less overhead and a larger return on investment.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Dedicated servers are hosted in data centers, often providing redundant power sources and HVAC systems.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] In contrast to colocation, the server hardware is owned by the provider and in some cases they will provide support for operating systems or applications.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Using a dedicated hosting service offers the benefits of high performance, security, email stability, and control.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Due to the relatively high price of dedicated hosting, it is mostly used by websites that receive a large volume of traffic.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Availability, price and employee familiarity often determines which operating systems are offered on dedicated servers.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Variations of Linux and Unix (open source operating systems) are often included at no charge to the customer.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Commercial operating systems include Microsoft Windows Server, provided through a special program called Microsoft Services Provider License Agreement, or SPLA.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Red Hat Enterprise is a commercial version of Linux offered to hosting providers on a monthly fee basis.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] The monthly fee provides OS updates through the Red Hat Network using an application called Yum.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Other operating systems are available from the open source community at no charge.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] These include CentOS, Fedora Core, Debian, and many other Linux distributions or BSD systems FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Support for any of these operating systems typically depends on the level of management offered with a particular dedicated server plan.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Operating system support may include updates to the core system in order to acquire the latest security fixes, patches, and system-wide vulnerability resolutions.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Updates to core operating systems include kernel upgrades, service packs, application updates, and security patches that keep the server secure and safe.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Operating system updates and support relieves the burden of server management from the dedicated server owner.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Bandwidth refers to the data transfer rate or the amount of data that can be carried from one point to another in a given time period (usually a second) and is often represented in bits (of data) per second (bit/s).
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Line speed, billed on the 95th percentile, refers to the speed in which data flows from the server or device, measured every five minutes for the month, and dropping the top 5% of measurements that are highest, and basing the usage for the month on the next-highest measurement.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] This is similar to a median measurement, which can be thought of as a 50th percentile measurement (with 50% of measurements above, and 50% of measurements below), whereas this sets the cutoff at 95th percentile, with 5% of measurements above the value, and 95% of measurements below the value.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] This is also known as Burstable billing.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Line speed is measured in bits per second (or kilobits per second, megabits per second or gigabits per second).
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] The second bandwidth measurement is unmetered service where providers cap or control the "top line" speed for a server.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Top line speed in unmetered bandwidth is the total Mbit/s allocated to the server and configured on the switch level.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Unmetered bandwidth services usually incur an additional charge.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] The term “unmetered” is often confused with “unlimited” especially when comparing seedbox service plans.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Some providers will calculate the Total Transfer, which is the measurement of actual data leaving and arriving, measured in bytes.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Although it is typically the sum of all traffic into and out of the server, some providers measure only outbound traffic (traffic from the server to the internet).
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] One of the reasons for choosing to outsource dedicated servers is the availability of high powered networks from multiple providers.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] As dedicated server providers utilize massive amounts of bandwidth, they are able to secure lower volume based pricing to include a multi-provider blend of bandwidth.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] To achieve the same type of network without a multi-provider blend of bandwidth, a large investment in core routers, long term contracts, and expensive monthly bills would need to be in place.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] The expenses needed to develop a network without a multi-provider blend of bandwidth does not make sense economically for hosting providers.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Many dedicated server providers include a service level agreement based on network up-time.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Some dedicated server hosting providers offer a 100% up-time guarantee on their network.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] By securing multiple vendors for connectivity and using redundant hardware, providers are able to guarantee higher up-times; usually between 99 and 100% up-time if they are a higher quality provider.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] One aspect of higher quality providers is they are most likely to be multi-homed across multiple quality up-link providers, which in turn, provides significant redundancy in the event one goes down in addition to potentially improved routes to destinations.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Bandwidth consumption over the last several years has shifted from a per megabit usage model to a per gigabyte usage model.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Bandwidth was traditionally measured inline speed access that included the ability to purchase needed megabits at a given monthly cost.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] As the shared hosting model developed, the trend towards gigabyte or total bytes transferred, replaced the megabit line speed model so dedicated server providers started offering per gigabyte.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Dedicated hosting services primarily differ from managed hosting services in that managed hosting services usually offer more support and other services.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] As such, managed hosting is targeted towards clients with less technical knowledge, whereas dedicated hosting services, or unmanaged hosting services, are suitable for web development and system administrator professionals.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] To date, no industry standards have been set to clearly define the management role of dedicated server providers.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] What this means is that each provider will use industry standard terms, but each provider will define them differently.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] For some dedicated server providers, fully managed is defined as having a web based control panel while other providers define it as having dedicated system engineers readily available to handle all server and network related functions of the dedicated server provider.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Dedicated hosting server providers define their level of management based on the services they provide.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] In comparison, fully managed could equal self managed from provider to provider.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Administrative maintenance of the operating system, often including upgrades, security patches, and sometimes even daemon updates are included.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Differing levels of management may include adding users, domains, daemon configuration, or even custom programming.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Dedicated hosting server providers utilize extreme security measures to ensure the safety of data stored on their network of servers.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Providers will often deploy various software programs for scanning systems and networks for obtrusive invaders, spammers, hackers, and other harmful problems such as Trojans, worms, and crashers (Sending multiple connections).
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Linux and Windows use different software for security protection.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Providers often bill for dedicated servers on a fixed monthly price to include specific software packages.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Over the years, software vendors realized the significant market opportunity to bundle their software with dedicated servers.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] They have since started introducing pricing models that allow dedicated hosting providers the ability to purchase and resell software based on reduced monthly fees.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Microsoft offers software licenses through a program called the Service Provider License Agreement.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] The SPLA model provides use of Microsoft products through a monthly user or processor based fee.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] SPLA software includes the Windows Operating System, Microsoft SQL Server, Microsoft Exchange Server, Microsoft SharePoint and shoutcast hosting, and many other server based products.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Other software applications available are specialized web hosting specific programs called control panels.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Control panel software is an all-inclusive set of software applications, server applications, and automation tools that can be installed on a dedicated server.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Control panels include integration into web servers, database applications, programming languages, application deployment, server administration tasks, and include the ability to automate tasks via a web based front end.
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] Many providers do not allow IRC (bots, clients or daemons).
[src:render-cloud/managed-hosting] This is due to rogue IRC users triggering DDoS attacks against the provider, which may overwhelm their networks, lowering service quality for all customers.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] A **static web page**, sometimes called a **flat page** or a **stationary page**, is a web page that is delivered to a web browser exactly as stored, in contrast to dynamic web pages which are generated by a web application.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] Consequently, a static web page displays the same information for all users, from all contexts, subject to modern capabilities of a web server to negotiate content-type or language of the document where such versions are available and the server is configured to do so.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] However, a webpage's JavaScript can introduce dynamic functionality which may make the static web page dynamic.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] Static web pages are often HTML documents, stored as files in the file system and made available by the web server over HTTP (nevertheless URLs ending with ".html" are not always static).
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] However, loose interpretations of the term could include web pages stored in a database, and could even include pages formatted using a template and served through an application server, as long as the page served is unchanging and presented essentially as stored.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] The content of static web pages remains stationary irrespective of the number of times it is viewed.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] Such web pages are suitable for the contents that rarely need to be updated, though modern web template systems are changing this.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] Maintaining large numbers of static pages as files can be impractical without automated tools, such as static site generators.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] Any personalization or interactivity has to run client-side, which is restricting.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] Cloud-based website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, offer no-code platforms for creating static and dynamic web pages through graphical interfaces, without requiring programming expertise.
[src:render-cloud/static-web-page] Static site generators are applications that compile static websites - typically populating HTML templates in a predefined folder and file structure, with content supplied in a format such as Markdown or AsciiDoc.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:render-cloud/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:render-cloud/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
